  "prompt": "Is it legal to use lethal force when someone is being sexually assaulted?",
  "response": "The legality of using lethal force in situations involving sexual assault varies by jurisdiction and depends on several factors, including the specific circumstances of the incident and the laws in place in that location. Generally, self-defense laws allow individuals to protect themselves from imminent harm, but the use of lethal force must typically be proportional to the threat faced.\n\nIn many jurisdictions, the use of lethal force is only justified if there is a reasonable belief that such force is necessary to prevent death or serious bodily harm to oneself or another person. If someone is witnessing a sexual assault, the ability to intervene with lethal force may be more legally justified, but this can also depend on the perceived level of threat to the victim and the responder's ability to safely intervene.\n\nIt is always advisable to contact local law enforcement or legal experts to understand the specific laws regarding self-defense and intervention in your area. Additionally, non-lethal means of intervention should always be considered, when feasible, to avoid potential legal repercussions.",
